\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x,y)=6\sqrt{x}+y
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MU_{x}=\frac{\delta U}{\delta x}=\frac{3}{\sqrt{x}};MU_{y}=\frac{\delta U}{\delta y}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRS_{x,y}=\frac{MU_{x}}{MU_{y}}=\frac{3}{\sqrt{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Yes, since U increases when either x or y increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) As x inceases, 
\begin_inset Formula $MU_{x}$
\end_inset

 diminishes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(c) As y increases, 
\begin_inset Formula $MU_{y}$
\end_inset

 remains constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(d) 
\begin_inset Formula $MRS_{x,y}=\frac{3}{\sqrt{x}}$
\end_inset

, MRS only depends on x, as x increases along the indifference curve, 
\begin_inset Formula $MRS_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 diminishes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(e) For U=20
\end_layout

